def list_file_extension(dataset):
    unique_file_extensions = []
    folders = os.listdir(dataset)  # list all the classes in the dataset

    for folder in folders:
        files = os.listdir(dataset + '/' + folder)  # list all the files in the class
        for file in files:
            _, file_extension = os.path.splitext(file)  # get the file extension name
            if file_extension not in unique_file_extensions:
                unique_file_extensions.append(file_extension)
    
    return unique_file_extensions

In [7]:
def load_data_from_directory(train_dir, validation_dir, test_dir, img_size):
    """
    Loads data from each dataset directory and returns the data generators for the respective dataset
    """
    # rescale all the images to [0,1] in float format
    train_datagen = ImageDataGenerator(rescale=1./255)
    validation_datagen = ImageDataGenerator(rescale=1./255)
    test_datagen = ImageDataGenerator(rescale=1./255)

    print('Training Dataset')
    train_generator = train_datagen.flow_from_directory(
        train_dir,
        target_size=img_size,
        color_mode="grayscale",
        class_mode='categorical'
    )
    print()

    print('Validation Dataset')
    validation_generator = validation_datagen.flow_from_directory(
        validation_dir,
        target_size=img_size,
        color_mode="grayscale",
        class_mode='categorical'
    )
    print()

    print('Testing Dataset')
    test_generator = test_datagen.flow_from_directory(
        test_dir,
        target_size=img_size,
        color_mode="grayscale",
        class_mode='categorical'
    )
    print()

    return train_generator, test_generator, validation_generator

def implot(generator):
    """
    Plots the first 4 images from the generator
    """
    batch_images, batch_labels = next(generator)
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 12))

    plt.subplot(221)
    plt.imshow(batch_images[0], cmap=plt.get_cmap('gray'))
    plt.title(f'{classes[np.where(batch_labels[0] == 1)[0][0]]}, {batch_images[0].shape}')  # display class name and image shape
    plt.axis('off')

    plt.subplot(222)
    plt.imshow(batch_images[1], cmap=plt.get_cmap('gray'))
    plt.title(f'{classes[np.where(batch_labels[1] == 1)[0][0]]}, {batch_images[1].shape}')  # display class name and image shape
    plt.axis('off')

    plt.subplot(223)
    plt.imshow(batch_images[2], cmap=plt.get_cmap('gray'))
    plt.title(f'{classes[np.where(batch_labels[2] == 1)[0][0]]}, {batch_images[2].shape}')  # display class name and image shape
    plt.axis('off')

    plt.subplot(224)
    plt.imshow(batch_images[3], cmap=plt.get_cmap('gray'))
    plt.title(f'{classes[np.where(batch_labels[3] == 1)[0][0]]}, {batch_images[3].shape}')  # display class name and image shape
    plt.axis('off')

    plt.show()

In [20]:
def image_class_distribution():
    """
    Plot a bar graph to view the distribution of images per class
    """
    class_distribution = {
        'Class': classes,
        'Count': []
    }

    for i in range(len(classes)):
        class_distribution['Count'].append(len(os.listdir(os.path.join('train', classes[i]))))  # count number of images per class
    
    df = pd.DataFrame(class_distribution)

    sns.barplot(x='Class', y='Count', data=df)
    plt.xticks(rotation=90)
    plt.title('Image Class Distribution')
    plt.figure(figsize=(12,12))
    plt.show()
In [21]:
image_class_distribution()

<Figure size 1200x1200 with 0 Axes>

As shown in the bar chart, the distribution of images by class is not equal. We will need to consider this when we are training the model as the model may be biased towards the classes with more images. Hence. we will need to use class weights when training the model to give more weight to the classes with fewer images and less weight to the classes with more images

We will only apply this to training dataset as the validation and testing datasets are to test and evaluate the model's performance, not to train the model which won't lead to much biasness

In [23]:
def plot_acc(hist):
    """
    Plot a line graph comparing the training and validation accuracy
    """
    plt.plot(hist.history['accuracy'])
    plt.plot(hist.history['val_accuracy'])
    plt.title('model accuracy')
    plt.ylabel('accuracy')
    plt.xlabel('epoch')
    plt.legend(['train', 'val'], loc='lower right')
    plt.show()
In [24]:
def plot_loss(hist):
    """
    Plot a line graph comparing the training and validation loss
    """
    plt.plot(hist.history['loss'])
    plt.plot(hist.history['val_loss'])
    plt.title('model loss')
    plt.ylabel('loss')
    plt.xlabel('epoch')
    plt.legend(['train', 'val'], loc='upper left')
    plt.show()

model37px_3 = Sequential([
    Conv2D(32, (3,3), activation='relu', input_shape=(37,37,1), kernel_regularizer=l2(0.0001)),
    BatchNormalization(),
    MaxPooling2D((2,2)),

    Conv2D(64, (3,3), activation='relu', kernel_regularizer=l2(0.0001)),
    BatchNormalization(),
    MaxPooling2D((2,2)),

    Conv2D(64, (3,3), activation='relu', kernel_regularizer=l2(0.0001)),
    BatchNormalization(),

    Conv2D(64, (3,3), activation='relu', kernel_regularizer=l2(0.0001)),
    BatchNormalization(),

    Flatten(),

    Dense(128, activation='relu', kernel_regularizer=l2(0.0001)),
    BatchNormalization(),
    
    Dense(15, activation='softmax')
])

model37px_3.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy', optimizer=SGD(0.0005), metrics=['accuracy'])

B. 131px Dataset¶

i. Base Model¶

As this will be our first model, I will not make the model too complicated with too many layers

model131px_1 = Sequential([
    Conv2D(64, (5,5), activation='relu', input_shape=(131,131,1)),

ii. Add More Layers¶

In [46]:
model131px_2 = Sequential([
    Conv2D(64, (5,5), activation='relu', input_shape=(131,131,1)),
    BatchNormalization(),
    MaxPooling2D((3,3)),
    Dropout(0.2),

    Conv2D(96, (4,4), activation='relu'),
    BatchNormalization(),
    MaxPooling2D((3,3)),
    Dropout(0.2),

    Conv2D(96, (3,3), activation='relu'),
    BatchNormalization(),
    MaxPooling2D((2,2)),
    Dropout(0.2),

    Flatten(),
    
    Dense(256, activation='relu'),
    Dropout(0.2),

    Dense(15, activation='softmax')
